'''Kamunazuka Kofun''' (加牟那塚古墳) is a [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] located in [[:en:Kōfu|Kofu]], [[:en:Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi Prefecture]], Chizuka. It has been Historic Site1 a Yamanashi Prefecture Historic Site under the name "Kamunazuka"<ref>{{Cite web|title=Yamanashi designation1 Guide (Database) Historic Sites 02|publisher=Yamanashi Prefecture|url=https://www.pref.yamanashi.jp/bunka/maibun/yamanashinobunkazai_shiseki002.html#SHI0019|accessdate=2020-05-11}}</ref>.

== location and Geographic-Historical Landscape ==

The tumulus is situated in central Yamanashi, at the northern edge of the {{ill|Kōfu Basin|lt=Kōfu Basin|lt=Kofu Basin|ja|甲府盆地|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofu Basin|qq=}}. It lies on the gentle slopes of the left bank of the {{ill|Arakawa River (Yamanashi)|ja|荒川 (山梨県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Arakawa River (Yamanashi)|qq=}}, near the boundary between Chizuka and Yumura districts. The area is part of the region known for its dense distribution of late-period kofun with {{ill|corridor-style stone chambers|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/corridor-style stone chambers|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}}, though many have been lost to urbanization.

Nearby burial sites include the {{ill|Manjumori Kofun|ja|万寿森古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Manjumori Kofun|qq=}} and the Yumurayama Kofun Cluster, as well as the Tengu-sawa Kofun, the largest stone-piled mound in Yamanashi Prefecture. The region’s toponym "Chizuka" reflects this legacy<ref name="#1">{{Cite book|title=Yamanashi Prefecture Place names|publisher=Heibonsha|year=1995|page=357}}</ref>.

During the [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]], this area was near the boundary of the {{ill|Koma District|ja|巨摩郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koma District|qq=}} and {{ill|Yamanashi District|ja|山梨郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanashi District|qq=}}. Archaeological evidence from sites like the Matsunoo Ruins suggests that this region was significant in the spread of Buddhism and political power during the late 6th to early 7th century.

== Excavation and burial goods ==

[[File:An_Kamunazuka_ancient_burial_mound_in_1910_%27s.jpg|thumb|240px|Kamunazuka Kofun in the early Taisho period.]]
[[File:Kamunazuka Kofun, 3D-B.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Overhead view of the stone chamber}}]]
[[File:Kamunazuka Kofun, 3D-N.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Layout of the stone chamber}}]]

Kamunazuka Kofun has been known since the Edo period. It is mentioned in the 1601 survey records for Chizuka Village and the comprehensive regional history *{{ill|Kai Kokushi|ja|甲斐国志|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kai Kokushi|qq=|1=Kaikokushi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11577871}}*, under various names such as "Kanazuka," "Kamazuka," and "Kamizuka."

Excavations in 1969, conducted by Professor Shoichiro Yoshida of Aoyama Gakuin University, revealed the tumulus's two-tiered structure, with a diameter of 45 meters and a height of 7.3 meters. The mound was covered with [[:en:Fukiishi|fukiishi]] and decorated with [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]]. The burial facility is a south-facing, single-sleeve corridor-style stone chamber built with large stone materials indicative of the late 6th century.

burial goods found include [[:en:Sue pottery|Sue pottery]], small glass beads, and three mirrors, identified as an [[:en:Flower mirror|Flower mirror]], a [[:en:Shinju-kyo|Divine Beast Mirror]], and a {{ill|Daryu Mirror|ja|鼉龍鏡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daryu Mirror|qq=}}. However, the location of these mirrors is currently unknown. Other finds include swords, shields, and various haniwa types, such as ceremonial implements, horse figurines, and warrior figurines.

Soil analysis of the haniwa revealed that most were made from volcanic materials sourced from nearby rivers, while some included granite, likely imported from regions like the Sone Hills.

burial goods from the kofun are housed in the {{ill|Kai Fudoki Hill|lt=Kai Fudoki Hill|lt=Yamanashi Prefectural Archaeological Museum|ja|山梨県立考古博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanashi Prefectural Archaeological Museum|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 曽根丘陵公園}}.

